            "answer_text": "The Sanskrit that we know today is written in a script called Devan\u0101gari. However this is the reference to the origins of the script till date.  Brahmi Script (B.C 250 - 150)  This is the script found on Ashoka Pillar is the common ancestral script to have off shoot from Harappa Mohenjodaro period (Vedic) up until this time, Vedas were only orally educated.  Gupta Script ( AD  240 to 550  )  We have some the great scholars during this period K\u0101lid\u0101sa, \u0100ryabha\u1e6da, Var\u0101hamihira, V\u0101tsy\u0101yana  Kalinga Script ( AD 590 )  Siddham Script (Siddham\u0101t\u1e5bk\u0101 - AD 600 - 1200 )  The famous heart sutra is written in this script. Primarily this script got off-shooted via Tibet to China and Mongolian countries N\u0101gari Script ( AD 730 - 1100 )  This was also the time the Assamese script sprang. While N\u0101gari script was primarily spoken around the northern indian regions, around the same time came another script primarily in the south. Nandin\u0101gari ( AD 770 - 1800 )  Used in the southern peninsula of Karnataka, Andra and Kerala \u015a\u0101rad\u0101 ( AD 800) Primarily flourished in Kashmir  Buddhist Script - Nepal (AD 980)  Around this time Bengali sprang up and Meithei Mayek script which was used in Manipur till 18th century.  Devan\u0101gari Script (AD 1100)   This is the chronological sequence of the evolution of scripts for a language that we call Sanskrit as on today. While the focus was primarily narrowed for Sanskrit lipi there was Kharo\u1e63\u1e6dh\u012b Sanskrit that was in vogue in the then Gandhara .  For more information  ",
